# API route rules

Keep handlers **thin** — auth, validate the JSON body, call `src/lib/clock/*`, serialize with `src/lib/clock/serialize.ts`, map errors with `jsonError()`. This app uses REST route handlers for mutations (pre-standard; no Server Actions).

## Auth

- Admin routes (workers, pending_uids, card_bindings, clock_events, stats, unassigned_taps): `await requireAdminApi()` first — checks session AND `ToolCardAccess` for `CLOCK_TOOL_CARD_ID`.
- Device routes (`/api/device/*`): `assertDeviceAuth(req)` — validates the `X-Device-Key` header against `DEVICE_API_KEY`.
- Cron routes (`/api/cron/*`): verify `Authorization: Bearer ${CRON_SECRET}`.
- `/api/health` and `/api/auth/*` are intentionally open.
- Never import Prisma-backed auth into `src/middleware.ts` (edge) — it only checks cookie presence.

## Validation

Manual field checks at the boundary (no Zod in this repo): required fields → 400 with a descriptive message. Device payloads use snake_case (`station_id`, `tapped_at`, `idempotency_key`).

## Responses

- Errors: `{ error: string }` with the status carried on the thrown error (`jsonError` in `src/lib/device-auth.ts`).
- Success: snake_case rows from `serialize.ts`; 201 on create, 200 on idempotent replay (see `device/clock_event`).
- Clients poll (`usePoll`) — no `revalidatePath`; just return fresh data.

## Cron routes

- `GET /api/cron/expire-pending` — expires stale pending UIDs into `clock_unassigned_taps`. Not scheduled in `vercel.json` (Hobby plan); expiry also runs lazily in the domain layer. If you add a cron, put the logic in `src/lib/clock/` and the schedule in `vercel.json`.

## Do NOT

- Put business rules inline in route handlers — they belong in `src/lib/clock/`
- Skip auth on any new route exposed to the internet
- Return stack traces to clients in production
- Break the snake_case response contract — the ESP32 firmware and `.jsx` pages parse it
